		{"id":"b96090b4fea6698f","type":"file","file":"_trace/_assets/839A4DB5-36E3-4D8C-B788-08795AE57FDD_4_5005_c.jpeg","x":6349,"y":-482,"width":400,"height":267},
		{"id":"5762fca44fafb084","type":"link","url":"https://chatgpt.com/share/69efbb6c-c0ec-83e8-846f-45aa53cdcc60","x":5540,"y":-760,"width":400,"height":400},
		{"id":"b464186ea910554d","type":"text","text":"> [!Iused one of clippings from the earlier full page gen,to get back to a groovier billy, i added Scroggins' adjustment and we got close (this image). then this last  prompt pushed it over the edge]\n> \n> ![[Pasted image 20260427154540.png]]\n> \n> great work.  ill take it.\n> \n> if i were to ask for charlie to feel smaller(he didnt tower over people) and more 'strange and magnetic' rather than warm in panel 2 im curious what you would do\n> \n> ==if you regenerate also try to emphasize the power lines in panel 3 and simplify the plantlife shapes into less detailed larger shapes (especially as they recede from fg==)","x":6962,"y":-800,"width":498,"height":267},
		{"id":"1c84e573d0c9348f","type":"text","text":"> [!Deciding to revisit page 4 for impact]\n> You did great.  \n> \n> Could we try something expressive/artistic for page 4? (where Charlie pills Micheal aside and asks the question)\n> \n> What if the darkness is more of an entity rather than a condition?  The bus could be ringed with Christmas lights (light ambience) or have headlights on or the girls can have flashlights  in  the bg.  \n> \n> We could play with silhouette and rim light and have Charlie be most visible and stark (gaunt too) when he asks the question.  (Panel2)\n> \n> And Charlie gets to walk back into the light of connection at the end while Michael stands out in the dark in panel 4\n\n\n\n\n![[Pasted image 20260427131815.png]]\n\n\n> [!Got the idea for the pool/spot light ]\n> Pretty good.  Could it be more flat ? Simply Stylized with how darkness and light are rendered?\n> \n> ==Maybe they have a pool of light== because of the bus and any girls are further in the bg with  a fire or their house or something\n> \n> We would also want the first and last panels to be much wider shots . The first should establish\n> \n\n![[Pasted image 20260427132505.png]]\n","x":6962,"y":-480,"width":505,"height":267},
		{"id":"a7e722a372486b22","type":"text","text":"Yes — the main difference was that I stopped asking for “cartoony” as a **vibe** and started asking for it as a **construction rule**.\n\nThis material naturally wants to collapse into:\n\n- memoir illustration\n- 60s counterculture realism\n- moody canyon naturalism\n- portrait-like Manson anchoring the page\n\nSo the successful move was basically:\n\n**Don’t say only “make it cartoony.”** **Say how the drawing must be built.**\n\n### **What changed**\n\nI pushed on four things:\n\n**1. Shape language**\n\n- big heads\n- simplified faces\n- gawky / bean-shaped bodies\n- oversized hands\n- iconic silhouettes\n- less realistic anatomy\n\n**2. Rendering language**\n\n- bold black outlines\n- flatter color\n- less naturalistic shading\n- less “illustrated memoir” texture\n- more cartoon-comix simplification\n\n**3. Character treatment**\n\n- not portrait realism\n- Charlie as a small, eerie cartoon center of gravity rather than a realistic likeness\n- Mike as an expressive cartoon observer\n\n**4. Page treatment**\n\n- dense comix page\n- hand-lettered captions\n- readable but lively panel rhythm\n- “underground cartoon tract” rather than “historical graphic narrative”\n\n## **The nugget to carry**\n\nThis is the kind of thing you can paste into future prompts:\n\n**Make the cartooning primary, not secondary.**  \nDraw everything in a simplified underground cartoon language: exaggerated head size, iconic facial features, gawky bodies, oversized hands, strong black outlines, flat slightly imperfect color, simplified environments, and expressive silhouette acting. Avoid portrait realism, painterly rendering, cinematic naturalism, and documentary-style illustration. Treat the page as a dense underground comix page, not a realistic historical reconstruction.\n\nAnd an even punchier version:\n\n**Do a shape-language transformation, not just a style overlay.**  \nRebuild all figures as cartoons.\n\nThat last line is surprisingly useful.","x":2772,"y":47,"width":388,"height":313,"color":"1"},
		{"id":"vault-ends","type":"text","text":"— vault provenance ends here —","x":2100,"y":-80,"width":240,"height":50,"color":"2"},
